mathew <mathew@mantis.co.uk> writes:
>pmetzger@snark.shearson.com (Perry E. Metzger) writes:
>> Incidently, this produces an interesting thought in my mind -- all
>> source code that you copyright is technically speaking available from
>> the copyright office (or at least part of it) even if you never sell
>> source licenses. Hmmm...
>
>Does this apply even if the copyright was not explicitly registered?

No, only if it was registered. However, this would mean that, for
instance, it would be possible to claim that any source code that was
registered could be claimed to be "Public Domain" information for
purposes of the ITARs even if the code itself is never sold.

